studentDS <- read.csv("StudentSucessDataset.csv")

Introduction (Motivation)

  • In todays dynamic educational landscape, its crucial to delve deeper into what influences student graduation and employment outcomes. Our presentation aims to unravel the complexities surrounding this topic by examining various factors that shape students paths to success. From demographic data to socioeconomic factors and academic performance indicators, well explore the intricate web of influences that impact student employment prospects.

  • The data set we are studying contains 4424 observations, in which each case is a university student. In addition, there are 35 variables that contain a variety of information regarding family, socioeconomics, semester information, and other demographical information.

  • Our response variable is Target, which describes the status of the students.

  • Using the other variables, our goal is to look at the qualities of some of the variables and create models predicting our response.

  • Our dataset is cited as: Valentim Realinho, Jorge Machado, Lus Baptista, & Mnica V. Martins. (2021). Predict students dropout and academic success (1.0) [Data set]. Zenodo. https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5777340

Mutate Data

  • Using information about the dataset, we mutated the dataset to include specific information for each categorical variable (excluding the Target).

GLM Section

Research Questions:

  • What variables are best when predicting the student status Target?

  • When creating a model with said variables, which are most effective when predicting the student status?

  summarize(
    N = n(),

    propDrop =  NROW(which(Target == "Dropout"))/N

Comments:

  • Looking at the plots and summary data, we find there is a higher proportion of female graduates than male graduates when comparing the two genders.

  • Similarly we find that there are a higher proportion of male dropouts than female dropouts, even though the number of dropouts appear to be similar.

  • This indicates that gender may be a good indicator for the student status or success.

Multinomial Model

  • For our Generalized Linear Model (GLM), we will be creating a Multinomial Logistic Regression Model due to the 3 levels of our response.

  • First we will perform a variable selection to find the best predictors for our model. Then, we will build our model using the variables selected. After, we will assess our model using overall accuracy as our indicator.

Load Additional Libraries

library(nnet)
library(MASS)

Variable Selection

Initial Comments:

  • We will perform a backwards feature selection based on AIC criterion, because we are interested in making predictions.

  • We are interested in minimizing our model complexity. And, this is method is automatic.

#Build full and base models
baseModel <-  multinom(Target ~ 1, data = studentDS)

fullModel <- multinom(Target ~ Marital.status + Application.mode + Application.order +

    Mother.s.occupation + Father.s.occupation)^2 + Displaced + Educational.special.needs + 
    (Debtor + Tuition.fees.up.to.date)^2 + Gender + Scholarship.holder + 
    Age.at.enrollment + International + Curricular.units.1st.sem..credited. +

NOTE: Given the Nuances in the Data (as seen in the correlation heatmap), it is a good practice to account for interaction terms when building the model.

  • Our Initial model before the feature selection included 34 Main Effects and 33 Interactions.

  • After performing the backwards selection we ended up with 25 Main Effects and 13 Interactions.

Modeling

Initial Comments:

  • Using the selected predictors we will create a multinomial model using the multinom function.
#Model using variables selected using backwards selection
bsModel <- multinom(Target ~ Application.order + Course + Nacionality + Mother.s.qualification + 
    Father.s.qualification + Mother.s.occupation + Father.s.occupation + 
    Displaced + Debtor + Tuition.fees.up.to.date + Gender + Scholarship.holder +

Additional Model

  • To further enhance our predictions, we are interested in implementing other machine learning techniques

  • Because of the high volume of categorical data and interactions, we were interested in seeing if using decision trees would be beneficial.

  • Specifically we will be using a bagging (bootstrap aggregated) technique call random foresting.

Load Additional Libraries

library(randomForest)

Variable Selection

  • For this model, we will use only the main effects selected in our multinomial model, since random forest decision trees handle interactions well.

MultiLevel Modeling Section

Variable of Interest: Unemployment.rate

  • Unemployment rates with the model will allow us to pinpoint demographic and socioeconomic factors.

  • Analyzing unemployment rates using a robust statistical model fosters institutional accountability.

  • The relationship between unemployment rates and academic performance indicators will help provide insights into the factors driving student success (our target variable).

  • Insights gained from analyzing unemployment rates can hopefully be used to inform the development of effective policies and programs aimed at reducing student unemployment.

This complexity can potentially lead to overfitting and difficulties in model interpretation.

  • Random Effects: Random intercepts are included for the effect of Course, indicating that there is variability in the intercepts across different courses. This acknowledges the nested structure of the data, where students are clustered within courses. The estimated variance of the random intercepts is 0.3195, suggesting that there is variability in the intercepts among courses.

  • Model Fit: The REML criterion at convergence is 19851.4, providing a measure of the models goodness of fit. Lower values of the REML criterion indicate better fit, although the absolute value itself does not offer a straightforward interpretation. However, it can be used for model comparison, where models with lower REML values are preferred if they provide a similar level of explanatory power.
